ressed some of the key ethical concerns of those traditions: the pursuit of truth and the ethical good, the ideals of self-knowledge and the care of the soul, and the relation of moral law to the tragic dimensions of death and desire. Rather than sustaining the characterization of Lacan's work as "anti-philosophical," these essays identify a resonance capable of enriching philosophy by opening it to wider and evermore challenging perspectives.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aPsychoanalysisxMoral and ethical aspects. 4aPhilosophy : Ancient Greek Philosophy. 4aPhilosophy : Hegel. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy. 4aPsychology : Psychoanalysis. 7aPSYCHOLOGY / Movements / Psychoanalysis.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438446509423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438446509/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles